<font color="#FF0000">LOCK AND LOAD</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jul 27 20:01:09 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook, you took to heart the &quot;ex-drug crazed Vietnam Vet&quot;. It was a shot at lame humor.  It is a discussion and at times humor is injected to make a point. The stereotyping came from all the news back in '65. It has become so trite that it is meaningless.  The comments I made about Doc Spatz was made because we have traded shots and have an understanding. Not by any stretch of the imagination do we have an agreement. I respect his beliefs, I don't agree with them. That is the first step in understanding someone's passion against the war.  Isn't it time to listen? We don't have to agree. We all understand about combat. Even Doc. Spatz.  This is non-productive.  I agree you saw a lot of combat. I agree you are a distinguished combat veteran. I agree that you should write a book.  I agree that there are some things that each of us can't abide.<br>
I did two tours, I was in the Ia Drang Valley in Oct.65 when we went up against the 66th NVA. I hope this establishes that I know where of you speak.  However, I was also a radio repairman, in an artillery outfit. To be specific the 3/18th it was 8&quot; s.p.'s and a batt. of 175's.  You have established your credibility. I hope I have established mine.<br>
And just F.Y.I. This site was put together by PBS and Marc Weiss a Viet Nam war prostestor.<br>
Chet Botkins<br>
RVN 65-67<br>
1st. Cav 3/18th Arty<br>
&quot;You can't be first but you can be next.&quot;
